@ksokolovskyi Thank you so much for your quick response and for taking the time to look into this — I sincerely appreciate it.

In my case, the issue still occurs when I run the sample code on DartPad using the Main channel.
Do you think I should switch my local Flutter SDK to the main channel and test it there?

Alright  @mycalls - I did my own testing and I think I can see some interactions that are going on but I don't know how to address them.

From what I can tell there are 2 things happening.

1) If the container is smaller than the available text, the scroll will be pulled. 
- In my code below, when used on my phone (Pixel 8a) in w chrome browser tab in dartpad, the rows of text go beyond the end of the available container and so are scrollable inside of it. When my cursor is below the line 6 the scroll is pulled down a _tiny_ bit and allows for all of row 6 to be nice and visible, cutting off part of row 1 as a tradeoff. This means that if I have my cursor on a line that would be below the container it seems like it will always pull down when visually splitting a line - but notably it won't scroll further down than the line that was being split. This means if your cursor is below the line you may never be able to scroll to the very top of the textfield.

2) As you add more lines (8, 9, 10, 11) the scroll pull seems to increase incrementally each time a line is added. For really long lined text fields I'd imagine it feels nearly exactly like being pulled to the very end. You also end up with a sticky cursor that doesn't want to leave the 'below the container bottom' position.

In my example you can actually test this. You can scroll to the top(ish) with 8 lines even though it does auto-adjust down to line 6 and cutting off line 1, but as soon as you add 2 more lines and get to 10, then we start to see the strange interaction where it pulls further down to the bottom and the cursor often becomes useless.

I think it has more to do with the number of rows and the length of the text in relation to the available screen rather than the text box being boxed in by a container that initiates a scroll.

